Right. Early in learning golang, many people will get tired of typing:<p><pre><code>    ..., err := doStuff()
    if err != nil {
        return err
    }
</code></pre>
The usual text editor features, like templates, reduce the typing, but the point is that the programmer must think, each time, about what they want to do when a function fails.  This can become either a really good habit, or a distraction, depending on your perspective and problem domain.<p>When people say Go poor or no error handling, this is probably what they are complaining about.  The fundamental properties offered by try/catch/throw are unpacked by Go into defer, recover and multiple value returns and type switches.  Go's designers make the argument that when used thoughtlessly, exceptions encourages error handling antipatterns.
